\subsection{Magnetic structure}
The measured and calculated intensities fron neutron diffraction at 320 K and 20 K are presented in figure \ref{NPD-refined}. As seen in the powder diffractograms, there are additional phases present in the $^{11}$B-sample. Most of the peaks that does not belong to the main phase ($\sim$5 \%) can be explained by small amounts of tetragonal boron ($a$ = 8.917(2) \AA, $c$ = 5.025(7) \AA, with the space group \textit{P$\bar{4}$n2} \cite{Hoard1951}). A second additional phase could be identified using a orthorhombic unit cell ($a$ =17.081(7) \AA, $b$ = 11.354(8) \AA, $c$ = 2.288(1) \AA, space group = \textit{Pnma}). This second additional phase could not be identified even though all reported binary and ternary phases in the Al-Fe-B system were tested, as well as their oxides, hydroxides and chlorides. 

